canonical:
  title: 入宋使臣上引伴使狀
  author: 金富軾
  language: lzh
  text: 右伏以寡君纂服職是守封上國馳誠禮當稱嗣嗟滄溟之阻闊加邊鄙之繹騷未抗表章已經年所玆膺使指底貢宸庭揭節戒塗已涉風波之險艤舟向岸佇瞻天日之光竊承逆勞之勤知有攀依之幸其爲竦企曷盡敷宣
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 入宋使臣上引伴使狀
  author: 金富軾
  language: lzh
  text: 右伏以寡君纂服。職是守封。上國馳誠。禮當稱嗣。嗟滄溟之阻闊。加邊鄙之繹騷。未抗表章。已經年所。玆膺使指。底貢宸庭。揭節戒塗。已涉風波之險。艤舟向岸。佇瞻天日之光。竊承逆勞之勤。知有攀依之幸。其爲竦企。曷盡敷宣。
korean:
  title: 입 송사신 상 인반사 장
  author: 김부식
  language: kor
  text: 엎드려 생각건대, 저희 나라 임금이 선업(先業)을 계승하여 봉지(封地)를 지키는 직책을 가졌으니, 상국(上國)에 정성을 쏟으며 예로 보아 마땅히 칭사(稱嗣 책봉받는다는 말)해야 할 것이나, 딱하게도 바다가 가로막히고 더욱이 변방이 소란하여 표장(表章)을 올리지 못하고 이미 해가 지났기에 이에 사신으로 뽑히어 궐정(闕庭)에 조공을 바치자니 절(節)을 들고 길을 떠나 이미 풍파의 위험을 겪었고, 배를 매고 언덕을 향하니 장차 천일(天日)의 빛을 우러러 뵙게 되었습니다. 그윽이 수고로운 몸을 맞아주시는 근념(勤念)에 입어, 더위잡고 의탁하는 다행이 있을 것을 알게 되었오니, 바랄 것이 없는 동시에 어찌 다 감사함을 아뢰오리까.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0510_010_0180&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Memorial Presented by an Envoy to Song, Introducing His Escort
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: I humbly reflect that our sovereign, inheriting the legacy of his ancestors, holds the duty of guarding the domain bestowed upon him. With steadfast sincerity toward the Middle Kingdom, it is only fitting by rite that he receive formal investiture. Yet, alas, the vast sea obstructs our path, and turmoil troubles the borderlands, preventing us from presenting our memorial. Already the seasons have turned. Now, appointed as envoy, we venture to bear tribute to the imperial court. With tablet raised high, we set forth on our journey, already having braved the perils of wind and wave. Our vessel now turns toward shore, and we await the radiance of heaven's light. Humbly receiving your diligent care in welcoming our weary mission, we recognize the blessing of having one to depend upon. What fortune fills our hearts—yet how can words suffice to express our gratitude?
  footnotes:
    - The 'tablet' (節) refers to the diplomatic credential carried by envoys, a symbol of their official status and authority.
    - The phrase 'heaven's light' (天日之光) is a metaphorical reference to the imperial presence and the sovereign's authority.
